  "summary": "Linn sits alone in a grove on a hillside, contemplating her potential marriage to Rolly. While she loved him before her enlistment, she feels she has changed significantly over the last four years, whereas Rolly remains the same. She worries that marrying him and moving to Long Willow would mean a life of stagnation and a loss of freedom.\n\nHer reflections are interrupted by David, who emerges from the bushes. David is in a hurry to catch a 9:20 train from Froebel to London to return to Rosaline. During their encounter, Lynn expresses contempt for Rosaline living in a serviced apartment, prompting a bitter outburst from David. He accuses Lynn of becoming \"tame and tractable\" like everyone else who seeks safety after the war. In a moment of intense emotion, David kisses Lynn and claims her, asserting that Rolly Claude is an idiot. He then departs, promising to call her once he reaches London.\n\nReturning home, Lynn feels confused and agitated. She reflects on her mother, Adela, who has borrowed £500 and views Rolly as a \"safe and reliable\" choice. Lynn feels resentment toward Rolly, believing that if he truly loved her, he would have provided the £500 she needed rather than being \"rationally and practically\" maddening. As she waits anxiously for David's promised phone call, she struggles to reconcile her attraction to David's volatile nature with the serene, predictable image of Rolly.",
